INTERACTIVE 3D MODEL VIEWER WITH REAL-TIME SHADING
COMPARISON
SUMMARY


DESCRIPTION
We want to build a 3D model viewer in C++ and OpenGL that covers the main parts of the
graphics pipeline we have learned about so far. The idea is that you can load an OBJ file, see
it rendered on screen, and then interact with it – rotate the model, move the camera
around, switch between perspective and orthographic projection, and toggle between
different shading modes. The core of the project is implementing flat, Gouraud, and Phong
shading so you can swap between them on the same model and actually see what changes.
We are also planning to handle visibility with a z-buffer, support wireframe rendering
alongside solid fill, and give the user control over a light source so they can move it around
and watch how the shading reacts.


IMPORTANCE
In class, we go through the math behind shading models and see some before/after images,
but we never really get to play with it ourselves. We think there is a big difference between
seeing a slide that says “Gouraud interpolates per-vertex colors” and actually dragging a
light around a model and watching the Gouraud artifacts show up compared to Phong. That
is basically what motivated this project – we wanted something where we could poke at the
pipeline and see the results immediately.
It is also a useful thing to have built. Understanding how the pipeline works at this level is
relevant if any of us end up working with game engines, 3D tools, or really anything that
renders geometry.


OUR PROPOSAL
We will build this as a desktop app using OpenGL 3.3+ with GLFW for the window and
input, and GLM for the matrix/vector math. Here is what we plan to support:

• Loading and displaying OBJ models
• Model transformations (rotation, translation, scaling) with keyboard/mouse
• An orbit camera with pan and zoom
• Toggling between perspective and orthographic projection
• Wireframe and solid fill rendering
• Z-buffer depth testing
• Flat shading, Gouraud shading, and Phong shading (using Blinn-Phong reflectance)
• A movable point light
• Stretch goal: texture mapping with UVs from the OBJ file, if we have time


RELATIONSHIP TO COMPUTER GRAPHICS
Pretty much everything in this project ties back to what we have covered in lectures. The
model transformations are the matrix stuff from the transformations lecture. Rasterization
and z-buffering are from Lecture 3. The shading modes and Blinn-Phong model come from
Lecture 4. Camera and projection setup uses the viewing pipeline. So the project is basically
taking all of those individual topics and putting them together into one working program.
Goals
Here is what we want to have working by the end of the semester:
1. Load and display at least two different OBJ models on screen
2. Let the user apply translate, rotate, and scale to models through keyboard/mouse
input
3. Implement an orbit camera with pan and zoom
4. Support switching between orthographic and perspective projection
5. Support wireframe and solid fill rendering modes
6. Handle depth correctly using the OpenGL z-buffer
7. Implement flat shading with per-face normals
8. Implement Gouraud shading (per-vertex Blinn-Phong, colors interpolated across the
triangle)
9. Implement Phong shading (per-pixel Blinn-Phong computed in the fragment shader)
10. Add a point light that the user can move around with the keyboard
11. Show some kind of on-screen indicator for which shading mode is active, what
projection is being used, and what the controls are
12.(Stretch) Basic texture mapping, if we finish everything else